!!Hoisted Variables

How about this

```
console.log(a)
let a = 3
```

What do you expect to get? A reference error, right? Wrong.  
So, it works as intended? Wrong again. 
It returns ``undefined`` because ``let a = 3`` is really two different statements, a declaration and a definition (or initialisation), which we do by "assigning" the value to it.

You could write the same thing like so

```
console.log(a)
let a
a = 3
```

It turns out that variable declarations, but not assignments, get //hoisted//, meaning that Javscript (actually the Javscript engine that lives in your browser and Node.js) treats them as if they were written at the very top of the //block// that they appear in.

